	abstract = {One important puzzle in international political economy is why lower-earning and less-skilled intensive industries te to receive relatively high levels of trade protection. This pattern of protection holds across countries with vastly differe economic and political characteristics and is not well accounted for in existing political economy models. We propo and model one possible explanation: that individual inequity aversion leads to systematic differences in support for trad protection across industries. We conduct original survey experiments in China and the United States and provide str evidence that individual policy opinions about sector-specific trade protection depend on the earnings of workers in sector. We also present structural estimates that advantageous and disadvantageous inequality influence support for trad protection in the two countries. One},
