@techreport{Peterson2022,
	abstract = {Does local news enhance the public's use of issues to evaluate their elected officials? While local media may inform the public about the views of their representatives, such coverage could also push people towards evaluating politicians based on personal traits or constituency service instead of policy. Local news also allows politicians to justify their stances, potentially persuading constituents to change their own views. Using an experiment and two observational studies we assess these competing accounts. We find exposure to local newspapers and television increases the public's use of issues to evaluate their representatives and see no evidence such coverage leads the public to change their own views to align with the politicians representing them. We also find that local media's contribution to policy-based evaluations of politicians has weakened in recent years, suggesting declines in the reach and resources of local media outlets limit their ability to serve as policy watchdogs.},
